1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,060
Once we set up our null and alternative hypotheses,

2

00:00:03,060  -->  00:00:05,040
we need used data to figure out

3

00:00:05,040  -->  00:00:08,765
which hypothesis we actually think is more likely to be true.

4

00:00:08,765  -->  00:00:12,780
And there are two ways we might approach choosing one of these hypotheses.

5

00:00:12,779  -->  00:00:15,419
One is the approach that we saw using confidence intervals,

6

00:00:15,419  -->  00:00:18,640
where we simulate the sampling distribution of our statistic,

7

00:00:18,640  -->  00:00:21,060
and then we could see if our hypothesis is

8

00:00:21,059  -->  00:00:24,419
consistent with what we observe in the sampling distribution.

9

00:00:24,420  -->  00:00:26,340
The second way we could approach choosing

10

00:00:26,339  -->  00:00:29,190
a hypothesis is simulating what we believe to be

11

00:00:29,190  -->  00:00:35,100
possible under the null and then seeing if our data is actually consistent with that.

12

00:00:35,100  -->  00:00:38,000
This is what professionals tend to do in a hypothesis testing.
